else clause is executed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Examine components produced on an assembly line, with success = 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

acceptable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and failure = 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

defective
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Bernoulli Trials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 0 denote failure and 1 denote success.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the sample space of an experiment involving 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 Bernoulli trials
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
S_{1} & = & \{0,1\},\\
S_{2} & = & \{(0,0),(0,1),(1,0),(1,1)\},\\
S_{3} & = & \{0,1\}^{n}=\{2^{n}\, n-\mbox{tuples of 0s and 1s}\}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For all sample spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

 we define the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma-$
\end_inset

 algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}(S_{n})$
\end_inset

 as the relevant 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma-$
\end_inset

 algebra on which to define the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 On 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 we then have 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\{0\})=q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\{1\})=p$
\end_inset

.
 We wish to assign probability to points in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}=$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

success on trail 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A}_{i}=$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

failure on trial 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 We then have 
\begin_inset Formula $P(A_{i})=p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\bar{A}_{i})=q$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 be an outcome of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

1
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n-k$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

0
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=(1,1,\dots,1,0,0,\dots0)
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Bernoulli Trials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The elementary event 
\begin_inset Formula $\{s\}$
\end_inset

 can be written
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{s\}=A_{1}\cap A_{2}\cap\dots\cap A_{k}\cap\overline{A}_{k+1}\cap\dots\cap\bar{A}_{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because events 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 are independent we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\{s\})=P(A_{1})P(A_{2})\dots P(A_{k})P(\bar{A}_{k+1})\dots P(\bar{A}_{n})
\]

\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\{s\})=p^{k}q^{n-k}.$
\end_inset

 Note that that we can construct 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 different outcomes with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 successes and 
\begin_inset Formula $n-k$
\end_inset

 failures, therefore defining 
\begin_inset Formula $A=$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

we observe exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 successes in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 trials
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(A)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k
\end{array}\right)p^{k}q^{n-k}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since by the binomial theorem 
\begin_inset Formula $(p+q)^{n}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k
\end{array}\right)p^{k}q^{n-k}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a well defined probability law on 
\begin_inset Formula $(S_{n},\mathcal{P}(S_{n}))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Bernoulli Trials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In connection with reliability theory let us assume that a particular system
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 components requires at least 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 components to function in order for the entire system to work correctly.
 Such systems are called 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-out-of-
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 systems.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $k=n$
\end_inset

 we have a series system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 we have a system with parallel redundancy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming all components are statistically identical and function independently
 of each other, and denoting by 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 the reliability of a component (
\begin_inset Formula $q=1-R$
\end_inset

 gives its unreliability), then the experiment of observing the statuses
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 components can be thouth of as a sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 bernoulli trials with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p=R$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
R_{k\mid n} & = & P(\mbox{"at least \ensuremath{k} components functioning properly"})\\
 & = & P(\bigcup_{i=k}^{n}\mbox{"exactly \ensuremath{i} components functioning properly"})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Bernoulli Trials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
R_{k\mid n} & = & \sum_{i=k}^{n}P(\mbox{"exactly \ensuremath{i}components functioning properly"})\\
 & = & \sum_{i=k}^{n}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k
\end{array}\right)p^{k}q^{n-k}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

